Lending Club Loan Data Analysis - Educational Loans

The following are some of the largest Fintech lenders: LendingClub Corporation, SOFI Lending Corp, Avant Credit Corporation, LoanDepot.com, Upstart Network Inc, and Cashcall. I looked at the two research papers and a different one I kept running into titled "Fintech Borrowers: Lax-Screening or Cream-Skimming?" by Di Maggio, Marco, and Yao, Vincent. I have attached the paper to the email that this is attached to, as well. In their working paper, they used the TransUnion dataset for various consumer credit reports and performed a comparison against Fintech lenders and traditional bank lenders. This analysis looks at loans granted for educational purposes. The data I will be using is the 2007-2015 Lending Club data for loan acceptances. There is a dataset for rejected loans that I will continue to analyze. Also, the dataset includes an "OTHER" category. Within that category, I will look for user-entered descriptions of their loan to identify if it could also fall under the "EDUCATIONAL" category. Additional features include credit scores, number of finance inquiries, address including zip codes, and state, and collections, among others. A data dictionary is provided in a separate file.

We will be loading the relevant libraries and Lending Club dataset.

Missing Values

Looking a summary of all the variables of the dataset, we can see that there is a lot of missing data for certain variables. As we saw before, there are about 2260668 enteries in the dataset. About half of the dataset only contains that amount. Some of these variables, however, are not relevant to our analysis. 'id' and 'member_id' are also missing all the values from the dataset I was able to gather. There are other datasets on the internet but do not have as many entries as this dataset. Futhermore, I would like to only analyze data pertaining to education. I will filter out the dataset relating to education as the purpose. All enteries seem to have this variable filled out so I will futher my filtering after the initial slice of the data.

total_entries = lending_club.shape[0]
perc_list = []
for purpose in purpose_list:
    num_loans = lending_club[lending_club['purpose'] == purpose].shape[0]
    purpose_percent = float(num_loans)/float(total_entries)
    perc_list.append(purpose_percent)

Break Down of each catagory

As we can see from the breakdown above, loans with the purpose of "EDUCATIONAL" make up less than 1 pecent of all the loans in this dataset. However, there is still about 6% within the "OTHER" category. We can utilize the 'desc' column to see if the text or description of loan describes anything regarding "Student Loans".

Limited Data

There is limited data in the Lending Club dataset regarding loans for the puposes of education. Less than 1% of loans in the dataset are for the purpose of education. Within the "OTHER" category, it is a similar case. Only about 7144 enteries of the 139440 entries catagorized as "OTHER" have a description. Within those 7144, there limited instances of loans regarding "Student Loans".

Numerical Values and Categorical Values

Upon my first initial look at the numerical values of the dataset, certain variables will require outlier manipulation. In other cases, certain variables do not have much variation.

  • tax_liens
  • delinq_amnt
  • chargeoff_within_12_months
  • collections_12_mnths_ex_med
  • policy code

We can also break down the limited dataset into two numerical and categorical values. After further analysis of the descriptions of each loan, individual educational loans can also be used for technical skills such as Yoga Instructor, Welding, etc. Some cases of loans within this category are also used to consolidate their student debt or to help pay for a few miscellaneous expenses.

# Distribution graphs (histogram/bar graph) of column data
def plotPerColumnDistribution(df, nGraphShown, nGraphPerRow):
    nunique = df.nunique()
    df = df[[col for col in df if nunique[col] > 1 and nunique[col] < 50]] # and nunique[col] < 50 For displaying purposes, pick columns that have between 1 and 50 unique values
    nRow, nCol = df.shape
    columnNames = list(df)
    nGraphRow = (nCol + nGraphPerRow - 1) / nGraphPerRow
    plt.figure(num = None, figsize = (6 * nGraphPerRow, 8 * nGraphRow), dpi = 80, facecolor = 'w', edgecolor = 'k')
    for i in range(min(nCol, nGraphShown)):
        plt.subplot(nGraphRow, nGraphPerRow, i + 1)
        columnDf = df.iloc[:, i]
        if (not np.issubdtype(type(columnDf.iloc[0]), np.number)):
            valueCounts = columnDf.value_counts()
            valueCounts.plot.bar()
        else:
            columnDf.hist()
        plt.ylabel('counts')
        plt.xticks(rotation = 90)
        plt.title('{}'.format(columnNames[i]))
    plt.tight_layout(pad = 2, w_pad = 1.0, h_pad = 1.0)
    plt.show()

My Thoughts

I think that that the Lending Club data is a great source to gauge fintech trends overall over broad categories of loans. However, I believe that it is not enough on its own. I will research into the TransUnion dataset that the research paper mentioned. From my initial analysis of this, I can see that this company is providing the "last dollar" loans.
